<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Esure</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">Written evidence from esure Group plc (CMI0009)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#000000; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:442.8pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#ffffff; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">esure Group plc is a top 10 personal lines insurer providing private car insurance to over 1.3million UK customers through its core brands, esure and Sheilas’ Wheels, plus the smaller First Alternative brand. We are active members of the Association of Bri</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">tish Insurers and represented on the A</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">BI’s General Insurance Council</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We submitted a detailed response to the original call for evidence by the Transport Select Committee and this paper should be read in conjunction with that response. In addition, we </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">also responded to the Ministry of Justice Consultation regarding the cost and frequency of whiplash claims.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">As a major UK motor insurer we experience first hand the challenges outlined by both the committee and the MOJ in dealing with fraudulent and exaggerated whiplash claims, the cost of which is a major consideration when setting premium levels for UK </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">consume</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s. Whilst we take the view that some progress has been made in reducing the costs associated with whiplash claims, there remains more work to do</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> particularly around tackling fraud.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We note the concerns of the Transport Select Committee</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> that there is a d</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">esire for clarity around how some of the proposals made thus far</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> will be taken forward</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. In addition, a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> further request has been made f</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> stakeholders to set out what more can be done to tackle the whiplash issue.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Whilst we have reviewed and contributed to</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> the response formulated by our trade body, the Association of British Insurers, this papers sets out our views on the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">key</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> issues arising from the debate for the consideration of the committee.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#000000; border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:442.8pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#ffffff; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Discussion</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Why is Further Reform Needed?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The starting </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">point when considering the way ahead is to look at the original motivation for trying to reform and improve the compensation system for genuinely injured claimants. The statistics speak for themselves in that the UK</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> population</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> makes a disproportionately hi</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">gher number of whiplash claims when compared to other</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">European</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> countries.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The insurance industry has long campaigned for a system with more teeth to tackle spurious personal injury claims and Governm</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ent has responded by making a number of</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> changes to the f</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">unding of personal injury claims. There can be no dispute that car insurance premiums have been falling over the last 12-months and the latest Confused.Com/Towers Watson Car Insurance Price Index points to a 13.9% reduction over this period.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Therefore, it</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> is clear that the ind</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ustry has been delivering on its promise to offer</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> lower premiums for UK </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">consumer</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s. This has been achieved despite increases in personal injury awards of</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> over 20% in the last 18-months alone.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">There is a clear need for further </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">reform if the savings delivered for consumers are to be sustainable in the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">medium term and we believe the following</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> are key </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">areas for Government to focus on</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Increase in the Small Claims Track</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We share the committee’s apparent view that the MOJ has been </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">too dismissive of the possibility of raising the Small Claims Track (SCT) limit given that such a small proportion of personal injury claims now fall to be dealt with under the SCT. The current limit has been in place since 1991 and the latest statistics s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">uggest that only 9% of PI claims are dealt with by the SCT.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">By definition, the SCT is designed and intended for simple, straightforward low value disputes. It is our considered view that straightforward, genuine whiplash claims do not necessarily require </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the assistance of a Lawyer and claimants should be given an alternative route to compensation. There is often scepticism when an insurer offers to deal with a claimant directly and we believe that the platform for the electronic handling of claims is alrea</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">dy in place and that this, when coupled with standardised medico-legal re</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">port</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, will</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> provide a solution that is fit for purpose and will deliver cost and efficiency benefits.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> The bulk of whiplash claims do not entail complex legal issues.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We strongly beli</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">eve that Government should look again at increasing the SCT to £5,000 and consider the solutions put forward by the industry that will address any concerns around access to justice. The solutions include:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">An improve</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">d system of</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> education so that the public</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> have awareness and visibility around how to make a claim, should they ever need to do so.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The mandatory use by claimants and defendants of a software based damages calibration tool ensuring consistent and transparent levels of personal injury damages.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> option of staff to be employed by the Portal Co to process paper claims for those without access to the internet or a personal preference </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to deal in paper.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We believe that this is the biggest opportunity missed by the MOJ and we would urge the committee </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to probe deeper into the decision to defer any increase for the time being.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Tackling Fraud</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">As </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">referred to</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> previously, we share the concerns of the industry that more assistance is need</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> in tackling the problem of fraud. The ABI is seeking </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">share great</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">er amounts of data with organisations such as </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the Motor Accident Solicitors Society (</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">MASS</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> the Association of Personal Injury Lawyers</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">APIL</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> Motor Insurers Bureau</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">MIB</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> and the Law Society but this focus is very much on facilitating the detection of fraud.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">A significant difficulty for compensators however is the way in which the Courts deal with fraudulent claims once they </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">have been identified and it is submitted that the Judgment in Summers v Fairclough Holmes (2012) highlights the barriers </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">faced by compensators. T</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">he Court concluded that</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> strike out of a claim on account</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> of fraud</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> is permissible but only at the conclusion</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> of the claim in </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">exceptional circumstances</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> by which point substantial legal costs have been incurred. The compensator rarely recovers such costs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We would like to see the law reformed in the area of fraud in personal injury claims with the default posit</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ion b</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">eing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> automatic strike out of a claim where exaggeration or fraud is proven. We urge Government to give approval to the Law Commission proposal to undertake further work in this area.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Progressing Reform of Medico-legal Reporting</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We fully support Gove</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">rnment proposals to reform medico-legal reporting in low value claims. A perverse system has developed whereby those preparing the reports are financially incentivised for firstly making a diagnosis of whiplash </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">and then arguably some will</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> secure greater le</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">vels of work by providing the lengthiest prognosis period. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">We are very much of the view that medico-legal reform is one of the easier issues to tackle given the apparent large areas of agreement between the ABI and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">MASS</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, the Association of Medical Report</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> Associations (AMRO) and the Forum of Insurance Lawyers</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> (FOIL)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">. We strongly advocate engagement and collaboration between the parties in order to bring absolute financial independence between the medic and those instructing them. Improved training and a sy</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">stem of accreditation is very much needed so that those compiling reports on whiplash actually understand the condition. Standardised instructions (including documentary evidence around the accident itself</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, reporting and a system of audit/peer review are </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">all essential elements of successful reform in our opinion.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Whilst improving the quality and accuracy of medico-legal reports is of paramount importance, the cost of medico-legal reporting is also in need of urgent review. Whilst informal agreements are i</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">n place in the form of the AMRO Agreement, there is general acknowledgment </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> fees are not enforceable and the Courts regularly depart </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">from these rates and award higher amounts. As with the level of legal costs payable to lawyers, the costs payable </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">for medico-legal report</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">s are now at artificially high levels.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> Referral fees were previously paid within the current fee structure, so it is clear that excess cost remains within the system.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> We support an evaluation of the true costs involved in producing a</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> medico-legal report and following consultation/agreement the level of fees payable should be fixed within the CPR.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Whilst we accept entirely that your recent call for evidence touches upon other areas outside the scope of this response, we have concentra</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ted on the key areas, which we believe will make a real demonstrable difference in tackling fraud, reducing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> frequency and containing costs.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:left;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>